97,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-27 23:47:54+00:00,74004167,Kyria/EsiPy,1838373,Kyria,,,290921673,361025303,"That's... interesting. I'm now wondering is assertRaises is the best way to check warnings... found this https://docs.python.org/2.7/library/warnings.html#testing-warnings 

This could be a warning behavior issue in py2.7/3.4 that, looking at your code above, you raise once / ignore once raised warning, and then it doesn't throw it again.
It'd probably be fixed if you try first the test with raise, and after the test ""i don't want to see anything"" (which is the warning behavior after all: raise only once, unless you specify otherwise) : 

```python
def test_esipy_expired_response(self):
        operation = self.app.op['get_incursions']

        with httmock.HTTMock(public_incursion_expired):
            warnings.simplefilter('error')

            with self.assertRaises(UserWarning):
                incursions = self.client_no_auth.request(operation())

            warnings.resetwarnings()
            warnings.simplefilter('ignore')
            incursions = self.client_no_auth.request(operation())
            self.assertEqual(incursions.status, 200)
```
Didn't test it right now but you get the idea. 
I'll give a review what you've all done and merge everything tomorrow :) 

Thanks ! ",{},OWNER,User,False
