430,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-04 08:05:48+00:00,44054354,dabeaz/curio,2698246,imrn,,,189325021,277427558,"On 2/4/17, David Beazley <notifications@github.com> wrote:
> If `Pause` is an exception, whatever task that raises it will simply
> terminate.    You won't be able to resume that task from that point forward
> (similar to what happens if a generator function raises an exception--the
> generator is done at that point).

Did you noticed this above?

except Paused:
    # _cleanup_task(current)
    raise

Do we still lose that task?
Are there any way to make it continue on the next run?

> The easiest change to make would be to have, as an option, something that
> makes `run()` return as soon as the initially supplied coroutine terminates
> instead of waiting around for everything else to terminate.   If you
> repeated called `run(None)` after that, whatever remaining tasks were still
> around would have a chance to run.   Or if you called `run(coro)` with a new
> coroutine, it would run until that coroutine terminated.

Ok. First things first.
Can you provide it so that we can at least have the emulation?
",{},,User,False
