The error code 16 coming from linux kernel is `EBUSY`, it looks like we get this in response(?) to `RTM_GETROUTE` (this run of the test suite, but it might appear somewhere else too, I'm not sure). It can come from [`ip6mr.c`](https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/master/net/ipv6/ip6mr.c#L1737-L1738) and multiple places from [`af_netlink.c`](https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/a8c199208cd68cc2d71684d84e37e3b56a2ae640/net/netlink/af_netlink.c) (it might come from more, we just got to these places)

I suspect something changed in the linux kernel, so we searched for EBUSY entries in the kernel changelog for EBUSY entries, but found no relevant changes so far.

Do you have ideas what/where we should look further?
",{},NONE,User,False
2217,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-21 17:27:38+00:00,9289343,svinota/pyroute2,689072,creasyw,,,73812955,123409315,"This is a flag which is included in the stations that are meshed up together. It does not have specific parameters to evoke, but comes with regular scan results when the I scan a station interface. The sample output looks like
```
root@eero-vega:/# iw sta scan | grep connect_point -B8
BSS 14:22:db:00:aa:28(on sta) -- associated
        TSF: 70730721558 usec (0d, 19:38:50)
        freq: 5785
        beacon interval: 100 TUs
        capability: ESS (0x0001)
        signal: -53.00 dBm
        last seen: 90 ms ago
        Information elements from Probe Response frame:
        SSID: connect_point
--
BSS 14:22:db:00:aa:27(on sta)
        TSF: 70735113324 usec (0d, 19:38:55)
        freq: 5180
        beacon interval: 100 TUs
        capability: ESS ShortPreamble (0x0021)
        signal: -20.00 dBm
        last seen: 2310 ms ago
        Information elements from Probe Response frame:
        SSID: connect_point
```
In the `nl80211.h`, the definition is:
```c
/**
 * enum nl80211_bss_status - BSS ""status""
 * @NL80211_BSS_STATUS_AUTHENTICATED: Authenticated with this BSS.
 *  Note that this is no longer used since cfg80211 no longer
 *  keeps track of whether or not authentication was done with
 *  a given BSS.
 * @NL80211_BSS_STATUS_ASSOCIATED: Associated with this BSS.
 * @NL80211_BSS_STATUS_IBSS_JOINED: Joined to this IBSS.
 *
 * The BSS status is a BSS attribute in scan dumps, which
 * indicates the status the interface has wrt. this BSS.
 */
enum nl80211_bss_status {
    NL80211_BSS_STATUS_AUTHENTICATED,
    NL80211_BSS_STATUS_ASSOCIATED,
    NL80211_BSS_STATUS_IBSS_JOINED,
};
```

Besides, the `NL80211_BSS_MAX` might not be included in the decoded items in the `NL80211_ATTR_BSS`. Because in the `iw/scan.c`, it has
```c
static struct nla_policy bss_policy[NL80211_BSS_MAX + 1] = {
        [NL80211_BSS_TSF] = { .type = NLA_U64 },
        [NL80211_BSS_FREQUENCY] = { .type = NLA_U32 },
        [NL80211_BSS_BSSID] = { },
        [NL80211_BSS_BEACON_INTERVAL] = { .type = NLA_U16 },
        [NL80211_BSS_CAPABILITY] = { .type = NLA_U16 },
        [NL80211_BSS_INFORMATION_ELEMENTS] = { },
        [NL80211_BSS_SIGNAL_MBM] = { .type = NLA_U32 },
        [NL80211_BSS_SIGNAL_UNSPEC] = { .type = NLA_U8 },
        [NL80211_BSS_STATUS] = { .type = NLA_U32 },
        [NL80211_BSS_SEEN_MS_AGO] = { .type = NLA_U32 },
        [NL80211_BSS_BEACON_IES] = { },
    };
```
and is defined at `nl80211.h` as `NL80211_BSS_MAX = __NL80211_BSS_AFTER_LAST - 1`. In turn, I cannot find other information for this `__NL80211_BSS_AFTER_LAST`.",{},,User,False
2219,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-24 21:45:02+00:00,9289343,svinota/pyroute2,814602,svinota,,,173055363,242218382,"The `operstate` parameter is provided by the kernel, and the library does not interfere with it at all. E.g., this is how it works for dummy interfaces:
```
>>> print(ip.interfaces.dummy0.operstate)
'DOWN'
>>> ip.interfaces.dummy0.up().commit()
>>> (ip.interfaces.dummy0.operstate)
'UNKNOWN'
```

Actually, to check the up/down state you can use `flags & 1` (`IFF_UP` from `ifinfmsg`):
```
>>> print(ip.interfaces.dummy0.flags & 1)
1
>>> ip.interfaces.dummy0.down().commit()
>>> print(ip.interfaces.dummy0.flags & 1)
0
```

There is also a static function to get flags names, though not public:
```
>>> from pyroute2 import IPRoute
>>> from pyroute2.netlink.rtnl.ifinfmsg import ifinfmsg
>>> ipr = IPRoute()
>>> print(ifinfmsg.flags2names(ipr.get_links()[0]['flags']))
['IFF_RUNNING', 'IFF_UP', 'IFF_LOOPBACK', 'IFF_LOWER_UP']
```

Or the same with IPDB:
```
>>> from pyroute2 import IPDB
>>> from pyroute2.netlink.rtnl.ifinfmsg import ifinfmsg
>>> ipdb = IPDB()
>>> print(ifinfmsg.flags2names(ipdb.interfaces.lo.flags))
['IFF_RUNNING', 'IFF_UP', 'IFF_LOOPBACK', 'IFF_LOWER_UP']
```

Why this way? 'Cause the the RTNL works so.",{},,User,False
