2226,IssueCommentEvent,2016-05-31 21:52:49+00:00,9289343,svinota/pyroute2,814602,svinota,,,157690702,222832674,"That's my mistake, I had to recognize the issue from the beginning :| My apologies.

No need to set up it, the issue is clear now. Actually, there are several issues at once.

1. The `bytearray` class changed it's API in some of early Python 2.7 versions, so now it supports the buffer protocol, and that's the cause of the backtrace on 2.7.3. But not the root cause. I didn't look exactly in which version the change took place, since…
2. The 0.4.x versions of the pyroute2 library do not support transparent bridge/bond management on old kernels. I stopped the CI testing of 0.4.x on RHEL6.5, thus ignoring not only the old kernel version, but the old Python version too.

The old kernels do not provide the netlink RTNL API to bridges and bonds, so they were managed there by pyroute2 via external utilities (while on the new kernels pyroute2 used RTNL only). But the proxy code, that managed these external utilities, became one of the performance bottlenecks, so I completely dropped it starting with 0.4.0.

Another bottleneck (and a memory consumption issue) was the buffer copying, so now the library uses `recv_into()` and `unpack_from()` to save the memory and to copy no extra buffers. But that makes it incompatible with old Python versions.

Thus, there are two branches of the library now, 0.3.x (LTS for platforms like RHEL, but w/o new features like rules management in IPDB) and 0.4.x (w/o compat code, fast and memory-efficient, but incompatible with old platforms)

And while I don't care about 0.4.x on old kernels, it still must work on (reasonably) old Python versions. I will try to find an acceptable workaround, if there is no way for you to use a newer Python version. And even then be aware that 0.4.x will not manage bridges and bonds on the kernel 3.14.

Thanks for such serious issue. Again, I had to find it by myself. I'm sorry.",{},,User,False
