2966,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-06 12:32:05+00:00,28453253,hughperkins/DeepCL,123560,hughperkins,,,168419973,238021215,"Ok.  That one is straightforward: jpeg is not needed for core stuff, so you can turn it off.  In the cmake window, there should be an option called `BUILD_JPEG_SUPPORT`.  Set that to `OFF`, and press `configure` again, and the warnings should go away.

BUT... the method I gave you is probably flawed.  I think you need to download the code using git.  This is a bit fiddly, but kind of has to be done...

- download git for windows from https://git-for-windows.github.io/ , and install
- open `git bash`
- the directoy system is a bit bizarre and linuxy... but you are basically in your home directory, even if it doesnt look like it
- do:
```
git clone --recursive http://github.com/hughperkins/DeepCL
```
- now, back in windows-land, you should see a folder `deepcl` in your home directory, and it should contain the latest code
- then just carry on as before, just using this code instead of the zipped/unzipped code.
(if you try using the zipped/unzipped code, I think you'll get errors about clBLAS missing and stuff, probably, anyway I havent tested that method; I *always* use the method I've just now just described)
",{},,User,False
