3203,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-16 15:24:12+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,56311,tobes,,,200613017,272890623,"@ultrabug @lasers to sum up my thoughts

@pydsigner have you any views on this?  You usually have a level head.

This issue is mainly about errors eg `No connection` etc. So I'll talk about them first.

My take is that an error is all that would be shown as the modules output, but maybe we do need to provide some info, about which module it is and maybe more, to the user. We could do this via notify_user() and that is my preference.

I also think that all errors should use `color_error or color_bad` so that there is uniformity.

I still like `error_..` for this because they have this distinct purpose (but I'm not ridged on this)

There is another usecase which is for static strings.  If these are for things like `N/A` and `?` but I feel we could use `icon_..` for this as it feels so similar to other places they are used.

I also think we should stick with the current `icon_..` configs to prevent user/developer confusion.  The name is not perfect but it does for now.

There are also cases like user notifications, but I've not really put much thought into those.  Maybe `msg_..` makes sense for these.

I think having namespaces for differently used types of config items is helpful

I believe too, that we should try to tackle one issue at a time like getting all modules to use `safe_format()` before necessarily solving this problem. ",{},,User,False
