4202,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-24 14:54:50+00:00,4978835,ulfalizer/Kconfiglib,154768,ulfalizer,,,353724407,415784205,"It's intended behavior, though a bit confusing here.

When you define a symbol/choice in multiple locations, you're still creating just a single symbol/choice, which gets the union of all the properties/symbols from the different definition locations.

In the `oldconfig` case, the interface is letting you pick among all the symbols in the choice (`choice.syms`).

In the `menuconfig` case, you're always just walking the menu tree. There, there are two different menu nodes for the choice. The first menu node (with prompt ""test"") has the menu nodes for `A` and `B` as its children, and the second menu node (with prompt ""more symbols"") has the menu node for `C` as its child.

The only special logic for choie symbols in the menuconfig interface is (1) how they're displayed, and (2) that selecting a choice symbol automatically jumps back to the parent menu.

What's shown between `()` in the menuconfig interface is still the selection of the entire choice (`node.item.selection`, where `item` is the choice).

As a side note, people sometimes (seen it once in the kernel) do weird stuff like having a symbol within a choice `depend on` the symbol before it, which makes it so that the symbol with the `depends on` is no longer considered a choice symbol (completely undocumented).

When configuring such a choice, you can end up with weird stuff like this, which shows that it's just the menu structure you're seeing:

![skarmbild fran 2018-08-24 15-29-07](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/154768/44587261-b48da880-a7b2-11e8-862b-3d5c4444677e.png)

It seems named choices with multiple prompts are broken in the C `menuconfig` (can't select the items from one of the definitions at all, and only the symbols that appear within the other definition), so no reference for behavior there. I don't think it would be too tricky to change it so that you can select all symbols at both locations. Not sure what makes the most sense there though.",{},OWNER,User,False
