4795,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-03 20:06:01+00:00,97002861,ljvmiranda921/pyswarms,39431903,whzup,,,331147757,402277104,"Ok, I see your point. But we still need to pass the topology information to the swarm or vice versa. How about we implement a new method into the topology classes called `assign_neighborhood(swarm)` (not sure if this works, if not there is [Python documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/faq/programming.html#how-do-i-write-a-function-with-output-parameters-call-by-reference) for that). You can pass in the swarm and it sets the neighborhood attribute in the swarm. We have to pay attention with the data types because the `Pyramid` topology cannot use a `np.array`. Additionally, we can implement a boolean parameter in the topologies called `static` and use it to decide if we want to assign the neighbors in every iteration or just in the `__init__` of the `Optimizer` class. Like so:

```python
if self.top.static:
    self.top.assign_neighborhood(self.swarm)
```
 in the `__init__` method so that the neighbors are only assigned once, and:

```python
if not self.top.static:
    self.top.assign_neighborhood(self.swarm)
```

in the iteration. @ljvmiranda921 do you think this is more approriate?
",{},NONE,User,False
