5568,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-05 22:20:14+00:00,50591651,danielperna84/pyhomematic,7396998,danielperna84,,,162335385,292014146,"@PatrickSteiner 
Not that I'm aware of.

@tonire1702 
There's a PR open for that one: https://github.com/danielperna84/pyhomematic/pull/64

I have never worked with OpenHAB, so I don't know how they are doing it. But I'm pretty sure they either do have implemented them all manually, or they use the XML-files used for devices, which in terms of licensing can't be part of pyhomematic. But that's all just a guess.
Either way, implementing devices in pyhomematic isn't hard at all. Most wired and wireless devices were implemented by looking at the documentation. The ones missing are either ones that no one would test (and are too different to just assume they are working) or which have no real coutnerpart in HASS. The HM-OU-LED16 for example needs programming to show colors. It's no problem to enable HASS to listen to the events those buttons generate. But people would probably expect to also be able to mess around with the colors. And since I don't have one and nobody else has yet mentionen how the device should end up in HASS, there's just no effort put into yet.
In the end it boils down to: we don't want to claim to support devices we haven't tested. And as long as nobody says ""I have device XYZ, make it do this and that, I'll test it"" no one will take care of it.",{},,User,False
