5601,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-24 23:33:29+00:00,40561035,hamiltron/py-simple-audio,11787806,hiccup7,,,164094015,262855924,"I have been using digital audio workstation (DAW) software and a lot of audio players and utilities for many years, and every 32-bit WAV file I have seen has been floating-point.  Few software apps even handle 32-bit PCM WAV files.  Python's standard library wave module simply does not support floating-point WAV files.  To keep simpleaudio dependency-free, I don't see how 32-bit (floating-point.) WAV files could be supported.

Python's standard library wave module does support 24-bit WAV files.  However, simpleaudio's goal of being cross-platform would be more complex because the default sound output device does not always support 24-bit.  16-bit is the lowest common denominator.  Does @hamiltron want to add the complexity of querying the sound output device to see if it handles 24-bit and converting 24-bit WAV data to 16-bit when necessary?

Users have the option of converting 24-bit WAV files to 16-bit with an external utility.  Users also have the option of using this package: http://www.lfd.uci.edu/~gohlke/pythonlibs/#sounddevice
It can be as simple to use as simpleaudio, but it is also very flexible.  It's dependencies are already included in scientific Python distributions like WinPython and Anaconda.",{},,User,False
