6044,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-17 17:30:29+00:00,5816230,michiya/django-pyodbc-azure,1220698,kdazzle,,,183452565,254275995,"Ah, I think I figured out why it's crashing on that line.

The line in question is:

`cursor.execute('SET DATEFORMAT ymd; SET DATEFIRST %s' % datefirst)`

The database that I'm connecting to is part of the Azure database warehouse and, according to [these docs](https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/sql-data-warehouse-connect-overview/), `DATEFORMAT` cannot be overridden.

![screen shot 2016-10-17 at 1 29 06 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1220698/19447970/be091e08-946d-11e6-9a5b-8e504e007da4.png)
",{},,User,False
6046,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-21 19:55:10+00:00,69611679,nshafer/django-hashid-field,3673047,nshafer,,,203446423,281461006,"Hey, sorry I missed this Issue, for some reason GitHub never emailed me about it, so I didn't see it until just now.

For my use-case where I'm using Hashids, I just use it to make the URLs pretty, and I don't rely on it for security. I definitely think that's the best way to use Hashids, as [it can be cracked pretty easily.](http://hashids.org/#decoding).

That said, I can see it being useful to not allow sequential scraping. I think changing the behavior of the field would be highly problematic specifically when it came to using the field as a target of ForeignKey and ManyToMany fields, so I'll have to think about this and play around with some ideas and get back to you.",{},,User,False
