6869,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-07 19:38:09+00:00,18031064,hmmlearn/hmmlearn,185856,superbobry,7037444,hmmlearn,158981843,224390553,"Hi, glad you find `hmmlearn` is useful!

> What do you think about using the framework for a classification problem with labeled data?

I think you can do this, if you agree with the assumptions: `y` are iid, `x` are `GMMHMM`.

* `seqlearn` allows you to model the data by a two-state hidden Markov model with some emission distribution. The crucial assumption `seqlearn` does is that the sequence of states the model goes through while generating `X` is known (`y`).
* `CustomHMM` on the other hand, does not assume the Markovian dependence for `y` and does label-specific density estimation instead. This scenario corresponds to supervised learning of a mixture with equal prior component probabilities and HMMs as component distributions.",{},,User,False
6870,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-25 10:44:03+00:00,18031064,hmmlearn/hmmlearn,185856,superbobry,7037444,hmmlearn,197488088,269117606,"Hi! As far as I know, boosting is well developed only for the case of supervised learning, while `hmmlearn` targets the unsupervised case. Take a look at [`seqlearn`](https://github.com/larsmans/seqlearn) which implements supervised learning of `MultinomialHMM`.

In general, it is hard to tell apriori whether boosting would give any improvement. The best way to find out is to experiment :)",{},,User,False
6873,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-21 02:36:55+00:00,18031064,hmmlearn/hmmlearn,5497193,luigivieira,7037444,hmmlearn,149669976,274227265,"Hi there @superbobry.

I found this discussion because I would like to use a GMMHMM in a supervised manner. I understand that I can not use seqlearn because my observations are not discrete. Your suggestion of using sklearn.mixture.GMM seems very interesting, but I don't even know how to start: I am new to HMM and GMM, and the documentation of scikit's GMM seems to indicate that the GMM is fit pretty much in the same way that it is done with hmmlearn: in a non-supervised fashion (i.e. without providing the labels for the samples).

Any help you could offer would be very appreciated. :)",{},,User,False
