7609,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-22 23:43:02+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,324506,Blystad,6117407,deis,95269797,123908645,"Hmm, so, if I understand correctly, you will first do a healthcheck at `HEALTHCHECK_INITIAL_DELAY` instead of attempting for up to 60 (configurable) seconds. Now, if, after `HEALTHCHECK_INITIAL_DELAY` the healthcheck fails, then the publish process will be cancelled, right?

With this solution, a user would probably have to configure `HEALTHCHECK_INITIAL_DELAY` at somewhere between 150% and 200% of the actual expected time for the first healthcheck. E.g. if I expect my application to be up and running in 10 seconds, I would configure this probably at like 20 seconds. (In case of new code slowing it down, or database migrations, or other stuff taking extra time). 

This would cause every new deploy to take extra time (20 seconds instead of 10 seconds), which is not a lot, but over time it does add up (+ it's annoying). 

OR, do you mean that you will first wait `HEALTHCHECK_INITIAL_DELAY` and then keep trying for `HEALTHCHECK_TIMEOUT`? 

E.g. if I configure `HEALTHCHECK_INITIAL_DELAY` to 10 seconds (as I expect the application to start in around 10 seconds), and then leave `HEALTHCHECK_TIMEOUT` at it's default 60s, then it will try to establish a connection to `HEALTHCHECK_URL` with 1s connect/data timeout for 60s?",{},,User,False
