8584,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-08 15:50:56+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,20861036,Travis-Taylor,12973369,dronekit,151760709,238280720,"@hamishwillee Yes, it acts in accordance with that behavior, of course. But the autopilot still responds to mode changes (for example, to and from **loiter** and **guided** modes), and while in **loiter** mode the copter should still respond to RC attitude input. I certainly don't want the controller to act on the RC controls during **guided** mode, but if I switch to **loiter** mode I want the RC commands to continue dictating the attitude of the copter

I say all this, but in fact the behavior I was observing is no longer taking place. To explain, I was trying to switch from manual control in **loiter** mode and then, at a certain point, switch to **guided** and execute a simple_goto(), then back to **loiter**. However, during this it either would not change to **guided** at the appropriate time, or would not return control back to **loiter** mode. However, once I properly removed all traces of the channels.overrides functionality from the program (controlling the copter strictly by RC controller), the switching behavior worked fine. Surprisingly well, in fact, considering the difficulty I was having in earlier testing.

Anyway, thanks for your quick response. Hopefully my problem will help someone else at some point.",{},,User,False
