9339,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-26 23:31:04+00:00,116516702,BYU-PRISM/GEKKO,5976666,loganbeal,33101889,BYU-PRISM,308235909,376345554,"GEKKO does clear the server on model initialization

```
    def __init__(self, server='http://byu.apmonitor.com', name=None):
        self.server = compatible_string_strip(server)
        ...
        #clear anything already on the server
        cmd(self.server,self.model_name,'clear all')
```
However, model initialization happens on m=GEKKO(). If you set the server with `m.server='http://127.0.0.1'` after model initialization, then this server is not cleared. Instead, set the server when you initialize the model `m = GEKKO(server='http://127.0.0.1')`

Nevertheless, the dbs and info files can get quite large since the server files append rather than overwrite. I have circumvented this in commit dd2b783335492c05a14c69714a543136ef7a4b0a by using measurements.dbs (rather than overrides.dbs) so the APM executable will clean up used options. Should I use problemname.dbs instead? 

> The DBS files are read next, starting with defaults.dbs and finishing with overrides.dbs. Most of the problem configuration information is stored in problem.dbs. This file is re-written every cycle and contains all of the information set by other DBS files or values that are adjusted by validity limit checks.

I also only write the info file when CYCLECOUNT<1. Since GEKKO doesn't support changing variable types, the information in the info file doesn't change. Even though there may be a few unsuccessful solves before CYLCECOUNT is incremented, this should at least keep the file at a reasonable size.

These changes are implemented in release 0.0.4rc1, released today. Please confirm the expected behavior on a remote server. ",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
