9521,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-20 23:12:37+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,27600,ellisonbg,7388996,jupyter,132012783,186699792,"A couple of thoughts:

In the short/medium term:

* Getting a full tree based file brower right from the design and
interaction standpoint is extremely difficult and time consuming.
* We are already building a brand new file newer for JupyterLab that has
many more features than the current one. The idea is that it would
eventually replace the existing dashboard.
* I don't think we have the capacity to have 3 file browsers in the
pipeline at the same time.
* My own feeling is that tree-based file browsers are more complex for
users.
* But, It would be possible for a third party to build a tree-based file
browser as a 4.x nbextension or JupyterLab plugin that is a separate
project that users can install and use.

In the long run:

* Eventually, after the existing dashboard file browser has gone away, we
may have capacity to tackle a more full blown tree view.
* In some cases, tree-based file browsers work better.
* A nice balance is the one in Google Drive, which by default is flat (like
ours), but still has a tree based view that sits along side of the flat one.




