9580,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-19 16:48:29+00:00,105712917,dwavesystems/dwave-cloud-client,447371,randomir,5449030,dwavesystems,303697960,374282625,"After ~#50, `ValueError` is raised only when (`endpoint`, `token`) pair is not defined after configuration loading.

That means this will fail:
```
>>> Client.from_config(config_file='nonexisting')
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""/home/radomir/work/dwave-cloud-client/dwave/cloud/client.py"", line 122, in from_config
    return _clients[_client](**config)
  File ""/home/radomir/work/dwave-cloud-client/dwave/cloud/client.py"", line 140, in __init__
    raise ValueError(""Endpoint URL and/or token not defined"")
ValueError: Endpoint URL and/or token not defined
```

But it'll silently pass if `endpoint` and `token` are defined with kwargs:
```
>>> Client.from_config(config_file='nonexisting', endpoint='...', token='...')
<dwave.cloud.qpu.Client object at 0x7f6dc00f5630>
```
or env vars:
```
$ DWAVE_API_ENDPOINT=x DWAVE_API_TOKEN=y python
>>> from dwave.cloud import Client
>>> Client.from_config(config_file='nonexisting')
<dwave.cloud.qpu.Client object at 0x7f8439867358>
```

This behaviour makes sense (i.e. `ValueError` == config not complete) because there are many ways of defining config file/profile (kwargs, env, autodetection, legacy file) and it's not completely clear under which circumstances should (perhaps) `IOError`/`OSError` be raised and under which we should just silence the config loading attempt and use the higher-priority values.",{},MEMBER,User,False
