9790,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-27 20:40:37+00:00,71482397,Parsl/parsl,7698139,ZhuozhaoLi,26490185,Parsl,350589333,416361184,"> Agreed, that's much better. Here is where I think we'd need the deepcopy. We'd still want the dedicated copy method though I think for the reasons outlined in the original issue.

After trying some potential solutions, I do not think we should add a custom deepcopy method to make deepcopy of the config, . Based on the [documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/copy.html) that `deepcopy() does not copy types like module, method, stack trace, stack frame, file, socket, window, array, or any similar types.` 

In the config (even we just specify the configuration), it already instantiates a new ThreadPoolExecutor, which includes the threading.Lock() and hence disallows the use of deepcopy. Making `deepcopy` and `load(config)` in this case returns error `TypeError: can't pickle _thread.lock objects` (same error occurs [here](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/14189#issuecomment-341633152)).

Below is the sample code you may try that returns the error.

```
import parsl
from parsl.config import Config
from parsl.executors.threads import ThreadPoolExecutor
import copy

threads = ThreadPoolExecutor(max_threads=4)
config_a = Config(executors=[threads])
parsl.load(config_a)
parsl.clear()

config_c = copy.deepcopy(config_a)
parsl.load(config_c)
parsl.clear()
```
Probably, to allow 'copy', we should create another identical config instead? Do you have any other viable suggestions? @benclifford @annawoodard 

",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
