9979,IssueCommentEvent,2016-07-12 18:12:25+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,6303703,dstaple,11668813,Z3Prover,165125974,232131699,"OK, fantastic.  For starts, here is the simplest trig problem I can think of that would be solved with such a tactic, which Z3 cannot already solve:
```
(declare-fun theta () Real)
(assert (= (sin theta) (cos theta)))
(check-sat-using qfnra-nlsat)
(get-model)
```
This would be converted to the equivalent of
```
(declare-fun x () Real)
(declare-fun y () Real)
(assert (= x y))
(assert (= (+ (* x x) (* y y)) 1))
(check-sat-using qfnra-nlsat)
(get-model)
```
which returns
```
sat
(model 
  (define-fun y () Real
    (root-obj (+ (* 2 (^ x 2)) (- 1)) 1))
  (define-fun x () Real
    (root-obj (+ (* 2 (^ x 2)) (- 1)) 1))
)
```

Regarding the symmetric nature of x and y in the fragment, besides the fact that `sin(0) = 0`, the other thing this fragment will never get is the 2*pi periodicity.  However, I think the symmetry breaking is only an issue when actual values are to be returned.  I think this can be worked around by returning models where `x` and `y` are left as `(cos theta)` and `(sin theta)`.  This allows us to benefit from the completeness of nlsat while maintaining the rigor of Z3 by avoiding numerical approximations of sin and cos that might come up otherwise.  I'm not completely sure how this would look when viewed with `(get-model)`.  I expect either statements that `(= (sin theta) (root-obj (+ (^ x 2) (- 2)) 1))` and `(= (cos theta) (root-obj (+ (^ x 2) (- 2)) 1))`, or perhaps a model containing temporary variables with appropriate definitions.

It would indeed be possible to encode the problem using `x` and `y` to begin with, but I think the number of trig problems that can be pushed into this category is larger than one might initially expect, if other rewriting rules and trig identities are used.  In the end, Mathematica and Maple are able to solve many trig problems that Z3 cannot solve.  I would love to close that gap, and I think this is a good first step.  In particular, statements about 3D vectors in spherical coordinates can be solved using this tactic alone.

I will build up a number of test cases of increasing difficulty and post them here.  If and when the tactic gets off the ground, we can clean them up and add them to the z3test repo.",{},,User,False
9982,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-21 13:19:09+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,511795,delcypher,11668813,Z3Prover,190614867,261936191,"@qingkaishi Could you try building with ASan? You'll likely get a much better backtrace.

