10048,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-06 18:54:57+00:00,30895522,pvlib/pvlib-python,4383303,wholmgren,11037261,pvlib,347667266,410815147,@cwhanse I think this is ready to merge.,{},MEMBER,User,False
10050,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-14 03:10:44+00:00,30895522,pvlib/pvlib-python,1125363,thunderfish24,11037261,pvlib,331820635,397156494,"@cwhanse @wholmgren  I am not necessarily proposing to replace _all_ the `calcparams_<modelname>` functions with a _single_ wrapper. Some sufficiently similar models may be consolidated (perhaps, desoto, pvsyst, and cec can be a ""family""?), but, as Cliff observed, I think that there may be sufficient differences between some models that combining them all may become quite opaque/complicated (e.g., my `F` vs. SAPM's `E_e`). I definitely see opportunity for this approach to make swapping in different auxiliary equations easier within a given model family, e.g., constant `Rs` vs. Kyumin's temperature-dependent model [here](https://www.slideshare.net/sandiaecis/08-kyumin-lee-cfv-singlediode-model-with-rs-temperature-dependence). Of course, I also have an eye towards automated optimal model selection from a dataset using multiple ""flavors"" of a model, and then pvlib models can more easily implement the various flavors.

As Cliff also points out, I think the assembly of the corresponding `**kwargs` would be hidden from the ""typical"" user operating at a higher level (e.g., the ModelChain), and there would be some method of high-level configuration that hides the implementation details. (I'm looking for ideas here!) A ""power user"" however would find a lot of flexibility under the hood, at the expense of less overt function calls. For example, a user should be able to swap in a user-defined auxiliary equation ""on the fly"", if they know what they're doing. Also, the design pattern _might_ readily mature into a more powerful computational graph method such as [Dask's delayed](http://dask.pydata.org/en/latest/delayed.html).",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
