10439,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-18 06:17:45+00:00,97507840,python-trio/trustme,42327,pquentin,26335827,python-trio,341412075,405821535,"So I don't really know how to debug this. The certificate chain seems to be valid. To check, use this new test script:

```
import trustme

ca = trustme.CA()
ca = ca.create_child_ca()
server_cert = ca.issue_server_cert(u""test-host.example.org"")

ca.cert_pem.write_to_path(""ca.pem"")
server_cert.private_key_and_cert_chain_pem.write_to_path(""server.pem"")
```

Running `python3 t.py &&  openssl verify -CAfile ca.pem server.pem` gives:

```
server.pem: OK
```

Yay!

However the test client from the end-to-end test still says: `ssl.SSLError: [SSL: CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED] certificate verify failed (_ssl.c:719)`, even in the stdlib case where [SSLContext.load_cert_chain()](https://docs.python.org/3/library/ssl.html#ssl.SSLContext.load_cert_chain) accepts [certificates like our server.pem above](https://docs.python.org/3/library/ssl.html#combined-key-and-certificate).

Any advice on a general strategy to debug this test failure?",{},MEMBER,User,False
10448,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-14 18:11:35+00:00,22072746,pantsbuild/pex,157586,jsirois,3065172,pantsbuild,148440348,210081700,This addresses #233 ,{},,User,False
10450,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-27 17:57:29+00:00,22072746,pantsbuild/pex,157586,jsirois,3065172,pantsbuild,105560530,408493964,"Wow this was old!

I hit this writing a pex unit test last night. The offending code is in [`InstallerBase`](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pex/blob/d1f946c8b46f8c5123b01bcd376c87bb67c8a884/pex/installer.py#L36). Right now , for the `WheelInstaller` we write out:
```
import sys
sys.path.insert(0, u'/home/jsirois/dev/pantsbuild/jsirois-pex/.pyenv_test/versions/3.6.3/lib/python3.6/site-packages'); import setuptools
sys.path.insert(0, '/tmp/tmpdzU0rv/interpreters/CPython-3.6.3/wheel-0.27.0-py3.6.egg'); import wheel

__file__ = 'setup.py'
sys.argv[0] = 'setup.py'
exec(compile(open(__file__, 'rb').read(), __file__, 'exec'))
```

Here - the sys.path.insert lines are randomly order by dict item iteration order, and the order show above is problematic, since `setuptools` is imported before `wheel` is on `sys.path`, foiling discovery of the `wheel` `distutils.commands` `bdist_wheel` entry point.

The fix is to just do all imports after we fully modify `sys.path`.",{},MEMBER,User,False
