11597,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-24 00:25:31+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,5071575,ltfish,12520807,angr,202366072,274662619,"> I think there should at least be a check and a warning if the CFG is not normalized, what do you think?

I understand why you are doing that, and that makes total sense. However, I think we can make this exploration technique generic in the sense of supporting an arbitrary control flow graph specific by user. For example, a user might want to break some basic block A to three pieces during symbolic execution, which is different from what `CFG.normalize()` gives you, and we should allow him doing that.",{},,User,False
11598,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-26 04:07:30+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,5071575,ltfish,12520807,angr,171456204,242625571,"`ULE(arg_l + arg_r, 0)` will be converted to `ULE(arg_l, -arg_r)` or `ULE(arg_r, -arg_l)`, depending on where the ""core"" (the unknown variable) is. Likewise, `ULE(arg_l - arg_r, 0)` will be converted to `ULE(arg_l, arg_r)` or `UGE(arg_r, arg_l)`. `ULE(arg_l, arg_r)` is just more natural, and in fact VEX IR generates a lot of such expressions. Without `Balancer`, only `ULE(arg_l, arg_r)` works. With `Balancer`, `ULE(arg_l - arg_r, 0)` also works, but it requires an extra conversion.

With that said, I think it's fine to have `ULE(arg_l - arg_r, 0)` generated from ccall handlers instead of `ULE(arg_l, argr)`. The only concern of mine is, that you might encounter more bugs in `Balancer`, which will be very annoying to debug :-)",{},,User,False
