11622,IssueCommentEvent,2016-07-05 19:30:52+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,830975,dovf,12520807,angr,142760934,230578442,"So does that mean I get to decide...? ;)

I've submitted a PR in vex, which is along the lines of the fix proposed by @ltfish: vex now returns a decode failure if an attempt is made to decode a branch or jump as a single instruction.

Regarding @rhelmot's concern about this occuring in other situations besides single-stepping (e.g., by a block that gets cut off exactly between the branch or jump and its delay slot): it turns out that vex already handles this case, just not if the last instruciton is also the first instruction (see commit message at https://github.com/dovf/vex/commit/2df16473f579a7963ff06c9175ceedea31cdeeb2).

The effect of this fix on angr is that now an attempt to lift a single instruction which is a branch or jump will return an empty block, with jumpkind 'Ijk_NoDecode'. Then, an attempt to step the block results in an exception (`SimIRSBError('Empty IRSB passed to SimIRSB.')`) which either causes the path to become errored, or immediately raises in exception (if `throw=True`). This situation can be detected, and then the lifting can be attempted again, this time with `num_inst=2`.

The problem with this is that it's not very clear from the exception raised what the problem actually was; I was initially tempted to detect the 'Ijk_NoDecode' in pyvex and to raise a more explicit exception (see https://github.com/dovf/pyvex/commit/2d30f73a828ea10121d86ddf65e4e5b6bd6cccfc). However, this caused some tests to fail (some pickling tests -- because the returned c_irsb is not pickleable, and the exception was being raised before that is fixed; this could be worked around by moving the exception detection until after the pickling is fixed, but... -- and some other tests which explicitly check for the no-decode case (because of corrupt instructions); these issues could probably be fixed by making the detection more and more specific to the specific case we're looking for, but that seems like too much of a kludge... So for the moment I think that just the fix in vex is good enough, or at least better than the current situation...

(This is my first foray into angr, so feel free to correct whatever's necessary -- and thanks for the wonderful tool!)
",{},,User,False
