11980,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-26 15:05:40+00:00,91356408,allenai/allennlp,3291951,matt-gardner,5667695,allenai,267380622,339696428,"I'd be a bit of a hack, but you could just save a reference to the whole sentence inside each `Token` object, then use that info in your `TokenIndexer`. It wouldn't be that bad to add a `context` field to `Token`, and let callers populate it however they want. We'll have to think about whether it's worth adding that to the official API, but the nice thing about Python is you can do it yourself with duck typing, even if we don't add it. If this isn't clear enough, I can give an example of what I mean.",{},MEMBER,User,False
11985,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-02 15:58:06+00:00,91356408,allenai/allennlp,11016329,easonnie,5667695,allenai,328383573,394097259,"Hi Mark,

Thanks for explanations. I see the problems here.

The current pipeline is:
RawText ---(Indexer)---> Text_with_index_fields ---(TextEmbedder)---> Tensor.
The `TextEmbedder` will combine multiple `Embedders` s.t. the final `Tensor` is the concatenation of all the embeddings.
Suppose we want Glove embeddings (300d), CNN Character embeddings (100d), and two ELMo embeddings (1024d), the final embeddings will have (300+100+2 * 1024d).

The pipeline that I want to build is:
RawText ---(Indexer)---> Text_with_index_fields ---(FlexibleEmbedder)---> Dict[str, Tensor].
where the final output is a dictionary of Tensors.

The output for the example given above will be `{'glove': g_tensor, 'cnn_char': c_tensor, 'elmo_1': e1_tensor, 'emlo_2': e2_tensor}`.

This could give downstream models the flexibility of using different word representations for different submodules.

Also, the current `BasicTextEmbedder` is a little bit constrained since *every* indexer_field need to be fulfilled by *only* one `Embedder`. In some use case, the same char_index_field might be used for different Embedder (like different CNN char model or two layers of ELMo).",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
11989,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-30 23:51:55+00:00,91356408,allenai/allennlp,5375447,julianmichael,5667695,allenai,355775470,417504383,"Anyway, just replacing the masked values (I did `top_span_scores[top_span_scores == float(""-inf"")] = -1.` and it worked fine) worked around this and fixed my problem at the end of the day. Maybe `replace_masked_values` is a bit cleaner so I'll go ahead and do that.

The `-inf`s might be something to watch out for in the future... since pytorch doesn't seem robust to them, these kinds of issues might crop up in other places as well.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
