12496,IssueCommentEvent,2015-05-29 04:42:05+00:00,26029828,ForensicArtifacts/artifacts,3888750,joachimmetz,3381114,ForensicArtifacts,81646820,106683689,Waiting for the tests but otherwise LGTM,{},,User,False
12507,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-21 02:08:13+00:00,68161929,oasis-open/cti-stix-validator,7005158,longdhnguyen,11744379,oasis-open,349752319,414526091,"Hello @clenk, yes that is what I'd like to have as an option or to have the script raising a warning for this. 

Also, I have found the exact part where you said ""I believe the STIX 2.0 specification allows referencing objects that are not distributed within the same bundle"":

**STIX™ Version 2.0. Part 1: STIX Core Concepts section ​3.2​ IDs and References**:

> ID references can refer to objects to which the consumer/producer may not currently have. This specification does not address the implementation of ID reference resolution.

This was sneaky since I expect this information is covered in the Relationship section :)",{},NONE,User,False
12508,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-03 21:39:31+00:00,68161929,oasis-open/cti-stix-validator,1045796,gtback,11744379,oasis-open,337741520,402299713,"Thanks for reporting this, @cyberfox1 . We ran into this issue in the stix-elevator. `validate_string` doesn't return a list of `FileValidationResults` objects, like `print_results` expects (instead, it returns `ObjectValidationResults`). 

Our [workaround in the stix-elevator](https://github.com/oasis-open/cti-stix-elevator/blob/5700eb5d9907bf2696b1bab32431f855dff989db/stix2elevator/__init__.py#L29-L31) was to wrap the `ObjectValidationResults` in a list of `FileValidationResults` before calling `print_results`.

Short-term, we should update the documentation to remove this invalid example. Longer-term, we need to update `print_results` to handle other types of input, or create other functions to accomplish the same thing. 

Thanks again!",{},MEMBER,User,False
12509,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-26 02:19:13+00:00,68160722,oasis-open/cti-pattern-validator,1045796,gtback,11744379,oasis-open,265453920,339530182,"I don't think it's fair to say `stix2patterns.pattern.Pattern` and `stix2matcher.matcher.Pattern` are *unrelated* (the former subclasses the latter), but indeed this only works because the actual classes have the same name and `__parse_tree` gets mangled to `_Pattern__parse_tree`.

As @chisholm points out, there are two decent solutions: convert `__parse_tree` to `_parse_tree` (effectively making it ""protected"" rather than ""private""), or leaving it private and exposing a public (or protected) `walk()` method. (We could also expose a ""readonly"" attribute using a public `@property` getter but no equivalent `@setter`). I guess I would be tempted to lean towards a `walk()` method, even though I don't necessarily see anyone else writing any custom listeners right now, unless they potentially want to expand on the functionality provided by the inspector.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
