13077,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-27 08:49:09+00:00,91379993,tensorflow/tensorboard,49262,jart,15658638,tensorflow,308224271,376446262,"If it's a documented feature in the manner you describe, then I agree it
should be restored.

On Mon, Mar 26, 2018, 11:39 PM Nick Felt <notifications@github.com> wrote:

> *@nfelt* commented on this pull request.
> ------------------------------
>
> In
> tensorboard/plugins/beholder/tf_beholder_dashboard/tf-beholder-info.html
> <https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/1075#discussion_r177321183>
> :
>
> > +        if (this._xhr.status == 200) {
> +          const response = JSON.parse(this._xhr.responseText);
> +          this.splice('items', 0);
> +          for (var item of response) {
> +            this.push('items', item);
> +          }
> +        }
> +        this._retry(this._getSleep());
> +      },
> +
> +      _retry(delay) {
> +        this._timer = window.setTimeout(this._load.bind(this), delay);
> +      },
> +
> +      _getSleep() {
> +        return 1000 / (this.fps === 0 ? 1 : this.fps);
>
> Please revert that ""solution"" - by removing the ability to set FPS to 0,
> you're removing a key feature that has been part of Beholder since Chris
> wrote it. It's important both to the UI - it lets you pause the video
> updates so that you have time to inspect the visualization and section
> values in detail, which is basically impossible at a 1 second update
> interval - and also to training performance, since by setting FPS to 0 it
> tells the actual Beholder code in the model to skip frame generation to
> reduce overhead during training. The feature is already documented in his
> readme
> <https://github.com/chrisranderson/beholder/blame/06a0cd4ffbda55e79a46ce98cd82ecc851523038/README.md#L129>,
> our readme
> <https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blame/70aece3b60800d872cf60cb0f4ab9a5dc1f94ed7/tensorboard/plugins/beholder/README.md#L134-L135>,
> and in his video <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=06HjEr0OX5k&t=114>.
>
> We shouldn't take away a valuable feature just because in an ideal world
> we would reimplement it using websockets (and as a aside, I still think you
> would want an FPS control for UX reasons as well as to be able to throttle
> down the generation overhead on the model training side, so I don't
> actually see how that would change things).
>
> If you're not interested in fixing the code to avoid XHRs when FPS is set
> to 0, we can leave it as is and I will fix it post-release.
>
