13260,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-20 06:43:02+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,3407345,CyberDem0n,1564818,zalando,351063845,414213036,"Patroni itself has no idea about your transaction rate.
If you don't like an idea of increasing `wal_keep_segments`, you have to configure wal archiving: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/static/continuous-archiving.html

Postgres on the replica will be able to fetch missing wals from archive.",{},MEMBER,User,False
13265,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-19 06:55:59+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,3407345,CyberDem0n,1564818,zalando,171952920,240942812,"How does your `archive_command` looks like?
It's very strange to keep archived WAL files on the same host where the master runs. If the machine dies you will loose them... Cluster (all database files) should be backed up to some external place and WAL files should be copied (archived) to some external place either.

Actually, the primary task of Patroni - implement automatic failover and some other tasks around it, i.e.: manual failover, cascading replication, provide health-check for haproxy or any other load balancer, provide possibility to reconfigure all nodes of the postgres cluster and so on. Backup&recovery is not something what Patroni could solve for you.

It's not an easy task to implement backup&recovery 100% right. Instead of inventing your own bicycle just use something already exists and proven to work, for example [wal-e](https://github.com/wal-e/wal-e), [pgbarman](http://www.pgbarman.org/) or [pgBackRest ](https://github.com/pgbackrest/pgbackrest). There you can configure your backup&retention policy, i.e. how long your backups and WAL files should be stored. It also will take care about removing old (unneeded) files. But in any case, all these backup&WAL files should not be stored neither on master nor on any replicas.

Actually it is not",{},,User,False
