13332,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-15 13:05:11+00:00,4235447,django-salesforce/django-salesforce,251738,hynekcer,9872531,django-salesforce,214359139,286735022,"Do you use TLS 1.1? (or any better)

Python versions supported by Salesforce (SFDC) are Python 2.7.9+ and 3.4 because TLS 1.1+ is required. See the README here (and thanks for version info, that the cause seems clear.) It is even easy to create a virtual environment with downloaded newer Python or other Python installed by Anaconda or compiled from source.

It is strange that you get the error only sometimes. I have no experience with backports.ssl. It seems that it is not supported good by `requests` package. You see that is an error in connection.close and connection.shutdown.

(It is still possible to leave old insecure protocols enabled on Salesforce setup, but not recommended and you will probably get warnigs every week that some old clients are still connecting and old protocols will be turn off soon without any possible workaround.)

Maybe an additional exception can be caught silently (if you can monitor the traffic at the time of error like lost packets, reset packets, timeout etc. and provide really many information) The problem is to decide correctly that the request should be retried. (It is not easy, because sometimes more issues are possible due to auto-repeat than by raising exception. If an error of the same type can be very frequent, then it is possible the account or IP address will be banned temporarily by SFDC after many ignored errors.) We use a variable settings.REQUESTS_MAX_RETRIES and requests are retried only by `requests` logic after timeout. It would require more investigation from you and finally it will be probably an issue for another package.

I think that we should not treat specific exceptions from optional packages if they are uncaught by urllib3 and requests and the nearest exception in the hierarchy is a generic `Exception`.",{},,User,False
