13785,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-14 18:06:03+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,6958867,dorodnic,14095512,IntelRealSense,195253635,267108113,"Hi, I'm not sure about the second questions, perhaps someone else will have the answer, but I can comment on the first:
When SR300 is used from its native software stack (Windows 10 + Intel DCM) the firmware is encoding hardware time-stamp inside the UVC-header, exposed through *Win10-exclusive* UVC-metadata API. This hardware time-stamp is absolutely crucial if you are doing any kind of depth to color synchronization, since using time-of-arrival would introduce visible misalignment.
On Windows 8, Linux and OSX, to the best of my knowledge you don't have access to the UVC-header, so librealsense is enabling an old hack the camera inherits from the F200: the firmware can embed 32bit timestamp into the first pixels of the frame. Same work-around exists on the R200 as well, however slightly more subtle. ",{},,User,False
