14259,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-07 10:27:58+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,293525,ijstokes,6392739,conda,48222854,128668251,"I just came back to this bug.  I think there is a smaller issue here which could more accurately be described as a bug: the package plan that is created *cannot be enacted* (offline), but in attempting to act on it conda will choke and die (stacktrace), leaving a bogus half-created conda env behind.  This is clearly undesirable behavior.  If the repo is unreachable *at the start* then there should be no attempt to enact a package plan and create an env which includes package downloads that will never happen.

Or put differently, perhaps the sequence needs to be reworked in conda: create the package plan, download any packages necessary, *then* try to create the environment.  Right now it appears that the environment is created first, so if there is a failure during the download process (and for sure there are *lots* of reasons why this might happen) then a duff env is going to be left behind.",{},,User,False
14260,IssueCommentEvent,2016-03-15 14:47:27+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,5345517,sebastian-luna-valero,6392739,conda,140171471,196851638,"
Hello,

Our travis builds are failing due to similar problem:
```
Error: MD5 sums mismatch for download: https://conda.anaconda.org/r/linux-64/r-acepack-1.3_3.3-r3.2.2_1.tar.bz2 (ba387b95acee58fa81e355e728c922ca != 37c504b279cb00d6bd45f2b27a15f92e)
```

We follow what is the documentation for travis:
http://conda.pydata.org/docs/travis.html

Specifically `conda update -q conda`. We could enforce the installation of `conda=3.19.3` but I guess that is a temporary solution and then we'll have to revert back to `conda update -q conda`.

What do you suggest?

Many thanks,
Sebastian.
",{},,User,False
