14276,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-20 16:58:15+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,180987,nouiz,6392739,conda,57548475,330915181,"@jkmacc-LANL I never read conda code. From what I know, you are right, all packages end up installed in the same directory and the env symlink link to them. As ""conda install"" compute the dependency itself for a specific env, he is able to get the information you want.

Why not have ""conda fetch"" call internally a ""conda install --download-only""? This would reuse much of the code while still having the not strange user interface? (This can be hard or relatively easy depending of the code, can't guess as I didn't try it).

@jkmacc-LANL My work around is pretty simple:
- conda create -n myenv_cloned --clone myenv
- source activate myenv_cloned
- conda install THE_PACKAGE_YOU_WANT

Personally, for the last line, I use ""conda update --all"", so having ""conda fetch --update-all"" would be what I would need. Which wasn't the exact same request from the original description.",{},NONE,User,False
