14393,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-20 15:11:01+00:00,613742,basho/riak-python-client,514926,lukebakken,176293,basho,160960046,227171611,"There's a lot of code in this issue, so let's narrow this down a bit.

* When you *store* a `datetime` in Riak TS, the Python client will convert that value to UTC milliseconds since the epoch, which is what you're seeing.
* When you use `ts_get` to fetch a row of data, *and* you use a `datetime` as part of the key, the Python client will convert that `datetime` to UTC milliseconds (you can see the test [here](https://github.com/basho/riak-python-client/blob/master/riak/tests/test_timeseries_pbuf.py#L439-L461)).
* When you use `ts_query` to issue an SQL query, all the `datetime` objects you use as part of the query must be converted to UTC milliseconds using the `riak.util.unix_time_millis` method. Riak 1.4 should support passing `datetime` values as ISO8601 strings to be converted server-side, but for now, you must convert the `datetime` objects to integers yourself.

So, in your case, can we get a simple set of `ts_store` and a `ts_get` statement that reproduces your issue?",{},,User,False
