14651,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-07 16:08:51+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,417568,craffel,11752110,Lasagne,99482403,128748755,"> Well, l_in_to_hid would need a ReshapeLayer on top that gets back to (n_batch, n_seq, ...). That one could also be added automatically if precompute_input == True.

It already reshapes back to `(n_batch, n_seq, ...)`: https://github.com/craffel/nntools/blob/recurrent_any_hid_shape/lasagne/layers/recurrent.py#L310

> It should definitely be documented that precompute_input=True requires a different input shape for l_in_to_hid!

Ok, I will document it.

> Everything else should be unaffected (i.e., the output shape of l_in_to_hid and the input and output shapes of l_hid_to_hid should all be equal, and all be the same no matter if precompute_input is set or not). It's not actually required to set the batch size to None, that's just the easy way out.

No, the output shape should actually be different when `precompute_input=True` (assuming the batch dimension is not `None`): `l_in_to_hid` should produce accept inputs and produce outputs with `shape[0] = n_batch*n_seq` when `precompute_input = True` and `shape[0] = n_batch` when `precompute_input = False`, while `l_hid_to_hid` should always accept inputs and produce outputs with `shape[0] = n_batch`.  I will add logic to check for this.",{},,User,False
14654,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-13 13:29:25+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,107537894,171289920,"> I would still keep the current recurrent layers.

Yes, we should refactor them, though, to get rid of the code duplication.

> If we let the user implement scan they would need to create three networks. before scan, inside scan, after scan.

If a single scan is enough for the network, that would be it, yes.

> I don't think that is too bad?

It still means the user will need to call `get_output()` and `get_all_params()` three times, as Lasagne doesn't know about the interconnections.

> In any case i don't think having cells exclude having containers.

Yes, we agree here :)

> Then this graph of layers, represented by the final output layer `l`, is passed to `CustomStepLayer(l)` which understands what the `hidden` key does, and turns it into a proper recurrent layer using `scan`?

That's not enough. The `CustomStepLayer` also needs to know how to feed the different inputs (the time sequences that are scanned over), i.e., which input layers of the graph are to be fed which sequences, so it can do the correct `lasagne.layers.get_output()` call on the graph. It also needs to know which outputs of the graph need to be fed back in -- these could be hidden states and cell states, but also predictions that have been processed by further feed-forward layers, for example. To the `CustomStepLayer` it wouldn't matter what's hidden and what's visible, this is just our interpretation of the outputs.",{},,User,False
