14679,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-14 10:29:44+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,100951214,131061657,"Nice idea! Seems very convenient. I'm just not sure whether it would be better to provide this functionality without having existing merge layers derive from a new base class. The alternative would be defining an `AutoCropLayer` to wrap any `MergeLayer` like this:
```python
class AutoCropLayer(MergeLayer):
    def __init__(self, incomings, layer, cropping=None, **kwargs):
        super(AutoCropLayer, self).__init__(incomings, **kwargs)
        self.layer = layer
        self.params = layer.params
        # process cropping as before
    def get_output_shape_for(self, input_shapes):
        # modify input_shapes as before
        return self.layer.get_output_shape_for(input_shapes)
    def get_output_for(self, inputs, **kwargs):
        # modify inputs as before
        return self.layer.get_output_for(inputs, **kwargs)
```

Then you could use it with any `MergeLayer` like this:
```python
l1 = InputLayer(...)
l2 = InputLayer(...)
l3 = AutoCropLayer([l1, l2], ElemwiseSumLayer([l1, l2]), cropping=...)
```

Hmm, no, it wouldn't work, actually. The `ElemwiseSumLayer` would have to be created with `AutoCropLayer.output_shapes`. We'd need to do a hack like:
```python
l3 = AutoCropLayer([l1, l2], None, cropping=...)
l3.layer = ElemwiseSumLayer(l3.output_shapes)
```

That's not really nicer than what you have. The cleanest solution would be stacking the `ElemwiseSumLayer` on top of the `AutoCropLayer`, but that's not possible because the `AutoCropLayer` has to give a single output and a single output shape with the current API.

So, well, maybe your solution is the best we can have for now! Any other thoughts?",{},,User,False
14680,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-29 14:36:54+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,192260009,263586450,"Neat! I've added it to the [Wiki](https://github.com/Lasagne/Lasagne/wiki/3rd-party-extensions-and-code). I suppose you're aware of http://twiecki.github.io/blog/2016/07/05/bayesian-deep-learning/? It basically just defines a custom initialization function for the existing Lasagne layers, so that it can use Lasagne to build the PyMC3 model. I'd be interested to see what the MNIST example would look like in your version.
Also I wonder if you could implement `gelato.layers` more generally, by checking which layers are available in `lasagne.layers` and creating the metaclasses on-the-fly? This way you wouldn't need to keep up with whatever changes in Lasagne.",{},,User,False
14681,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-03 20:20:09+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,544718,ebenolson,11752110,Lasagne,84571522,108603292,"I'm not sure about using `weights` in the name, isn't the point of the `regularizable` tag that there could in theory be regularizable parameters that aren't weights?

I also somewhat prefer names like `cost`, `loss` or `penalty` to `penalize` or `regularize`, because the function is just giving us an expression, not actually performing an action on the network. 

