14855,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-06 14:21:28+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,185007,dkirkby,1462196,GalSim-developers,66334010,90080315,"> The point is that lambda / D is not dimensionless. It is an angle.

There's an important distinction between dimensions and units here:  (lambda/D), ""1 arcsec"", and ""0.001 deg"" are all dimensionless, but have [different units of dimension 1](http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP811/sec07.html#7.10).  It is certainly possible to allow dimensionless quantities to be provided in different units. For example, you could allow Sersic indices to be input in % or ppm. However, my point is that this is not intuitive (since dimensionless quantities are unique in having a single 'natural' unit) and likely to be error prone unless the API includes some additional book keeping (e.g., require that lambda/D be multiplied by an AngleUnit, like other angles in GalSim).",{},,User,False
14858,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-07 16:00:48+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,623887,rmjarvis,1462196,GalSim-developers,193887968,265487247,"That's probably where libpython*.so lives, so it needs to be there for the loadable module.  TMV worked when it compiled a standalone program.  The failure here is when it's included as part of a python loadable module.

My guess is that you'll either need to recompile TMV to use the anaconda stdc++ library or update the system one to be compatible with it.",{},,User,False
