14869,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-28 02:10:23+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,623887,rmjarvis,1462196,GalSim-developers,354513868,416427415,"I agree this is rather unfortunate behavior.  

But I'll point out that this only happens when drawing onto a single-precision Image.  If you do `conv.drawImage(scale=0.2, dtype=float)`, it can handle it fine.  The problem is that you are having it draw first with 1.e-60, then scaling it up by a factor of 1.e50.  These operations are problematic at single precision.

So is this an important use case that you think needs fixing?  Or just something that is an interesting by-product of the implementation details of how GalSIm draws images?",{},MEMBER,User,False
14872,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-19 02:37:39+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,623887,rmjarvis,1462196,GalSim-developers,134740339,186020874,"Not quite.  Although, you're right that this line is wrong.  The correct formula is
```
sky_level / gain + (read_noise / gain)**2
```
And I agree with you about the definition of gain being weird.  ADU/e- would be much more natural, but e-/ADU is the standard definition for astronomy detectors.  Or CCDs at least.  cf. http://www.mirametrics.com/tech_note_ccdgain.htm

Unfortunately, it looks like our unit test of this function just checked that the output was this formula, rather than adding noise to an image and checking that the variance was right (or close).  I just did that, and the variance is indeed close to the formula I gave, but not close to `ccd_noise.getVariance()`.  I'll fix this and update the unit test.",{},,User,False
