",{},NONE,User,False
15724,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-24 09:03:04+00:00,40094312,pyserial/pyserial,159819,cefn,10537924,pyserial,317132192,383858657,"For reference, this was a remaining issue after https://github.com/pyserial/pyserial/issues/238 resolved most other issues relating to command codes, but linefeed issue remained. Sorry not to remember this was also reported as part of that original issue. 

I will report more detail on the use of the --eol flag which was mentioned.",{},NONE,User,False
15725,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-12 20:48:47+00:00,40094312,pyserial/pyserial,1796161,rdpoor,10537924,pyserial,331215882,396728724,"@zsquareplusc : 

First, an apology and correction: I neglected to show the `sleep(0.002)` in my code following the `read()`.  (I'll go back and correct the original.)

But that doesn't really address your comment.  I'm certainly open to using a blocking read if it can be made to work for this application.  But my choice for a non-blocking read was a very conscious decision: if you're familiar with the Modbus RTU spec, you already know that the end of a Modbus packet is signaled by a gap of 3.5 BIT periods.  You don't know the packet length ahead of time, there's no end-of-frame byte.  And to put it in perspective, 3.5 bit periods at 19.2Kbaud is 156 microseconds (!!).  

My first approach was to use `serial.inter_byte_timeout` to detect end-of-packet, but that doesn't work since its minimum value is 100 milliseconds (and anything less than that is treated as zero).  I  also groveled over the sources for `serial.threaded` and write a number of sketches using `serial.threaded` and variants, but my main takeaway is that by the time you do a context switch, you've already lost the game.  

So ultimately I chose a single threaded approach.  Yes, this approach ties up the GIL while waiting for a packet. But the mitigating factors include:

- Mine is a command line app, so there are no other events pending while this is going on.
- The Modbus spec is a strict master/slave protocol: after sending a request, the Master isn't *allowed* to do anything else until it gets a response from the slave (or a timeout)
-  The timeouts are small.  As I mentioned, the end-of-packet gap is measured in microseconds, a typical request/response timeout is a tenth of a second.

Thoughts?















",{},NONE,User,False
