16133,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-08 21:13:34+00:00,3060959,certifi/python-certifi,1382556,Lukasa,7292629,certifi,212857157,285170965,"That makes this a duplicate of #26: see [this blog post](https://lukasa.co.uk/2015/04/Certifi_State_Of_Union/) for more. To resolve this issue you'll either need to do `requests.get(url, verify=certifi.old_where())`, or upgrade to OpenSSL 1.0.2 or later. I *strongly* recommend doing the latter, as the former is insecure and will eventually be removed from certifi.",{},,User,False
16134,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-12 17:23:42+00:00,3060959,certifi/python-certifi,1382556,Lukasa,7292629,certifi,87769298,111565295,"> Also, isn't it best practice to be running inside of a virtualenv?

Yes. Sadly, security-critical infrastructure should not assume best-practices. =(

Temporary files on disk work, but I'm more interested in being able to build an in-memory PEM database. That'd be a good feature for certifi anyway, so if we can make OpenSSL shut up and take them I'd vastly prefer to take that path.",{},,User,False
