16281,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-07 11:57:04+00:00,440043,jazzband/django-axes,2477934,aleksihakli,15129049,jazzband,285461605,355817563,"Hey, `django-ipware` indeed seems to be somewhat prone to proxy header injection and doesn't have the number of known proxies configurable. I previously contributed #225 which fixed IP address resolving by calculating the IP based on the number of proxies in the proxy chains, but using `django-ipware` scrubs this. Configuration for number of proxies is useful in e.g. AWS where there might be requests coming in directly to the web server reverse proxy whereas we would want request to flow through load balancers and into the web server; the configuration for the number fixes this and filters out unwanted requests with invalid headers.

It also seems that `django-ipware` also has a conflicted definition of how to use the proxy headers as seen here:

https://github.com/un33k/django-ipware/blob/master/ipware/defaults.py#L11

Whereas X-Forwarded-For should set the client IP as first address:

https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/X-Forwarded-For

There of course could be proxies that set the client IP as the last address but that would not be the de-facto standard way.

[I've opening an issue on the `django-ipware` for some further discussion on the matter](https://github.com/un33k/django-ipware/issues/33). Resolving IPs is smart to do in a specialized module, I think, and the development effort should be proxied there and documentation improved here :) Keeping things DRY will improve the life for everybody and `django-ipware` seems to have an active maintainer.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
