16412,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-08 04:41:56+00:00,71932349,ray-project/ray,14922,ericl,22125274,ray-project,229461464,306996519,"When this happens, the local_scheduler process is stuck at 100% cpu, and appears to be spending most of its time in `common/thirdparty/ae/ae.c:aeDeleteTimeEvent()`. It looks like each call to `aeDeleteTimeEvent()` scans the entire event queue, so assuming you eventually want to delete each event, the overall CPU used for event processing is going to grow O(n^2) wrt the size of the queue.

Because of this n^2 thing, I think that launching enough tasks is making event processing *slow enough* that the event queue grows unboundedly. Indeed it seems that once the queue size hits >6k events, it does start growing unboundedly and you get the retry messages.

TLDR: I think event processing is O(n^2) and can't keep up if there are too many tasks. Thoughts on angle of attack?",{},,User,False
