16623,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-14 08:25:36+00:00,66641037,LonamiWebs/Telethon,6297805,Lonami,9887454,LonamiWebs,228515067,301298111,"> It's not a crucial issue

Maybe you just pinpointed something more important, though. Notice, the only definitions using **v**ector are, as you said, [`future_salts`](https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop/blob/dev/Telegram/Resources/scheme.tl#L93), but **also** [`msg_container`](https://github.com/telegramdesktop/tdesktop/blob/dev/Telegram/Resources/scheme.tl#L103). What's so special about the later? That you [don't read](https://github.com/LonamiWebs/Telethon/blob/048bc81b74471796a7ba3111ddbe04035a0ddd05/telethon/network/mtproto_sender.py#L290) the vector code (only the `handle_container` code itself). So maybe Telegram does a distinction indeed (and since these two are so ""special"", maybe they just stopped updating the `.tl` to reflect it because it's commented anyway, or maybe they mention it (but then why another type for the vector?)).

I was going to try to invoke [`GetFutureSaltsRequest`](https://lonamiwebs.github.io/Telethon/methods/get_future_salts.html), but I don't know what that `num` parameter is. Perhaps when Telegram server sent it, as shown [here](https://github.com/sochix/TLSharp/blob/ca6e18b50ea7cab777ae0a49e1a7097dc1ae2583/TLSharp.Core/Network/MtProtoSender.cs#L186-L188).",{},,User,False
16626,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-23 07:41:49+00:00,66641037,LonamiWebs/Telethon,6297805,Lonami,9887454,LonamiWebs,230572341,303316343,"> ```python
> entity = update_object.user_id
> # …
> peer=get_input_peer(entity)
> ```

You cannot do that. `get_input_peer` can't work with integer values (`user_id`) because it needs more information (namely, `access_hash`), so it returns `None`. It should probably raise a better error.

So first retrieve the user per se, or store or somewhere to then look it up by its ID, or any other approach should work. But you need to pass an `User` to get the `InputUser` from that function.",{},,User,False
