16641,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-05 23:44:12+00:00,46293472,Backblaze/B2_Command_Line_Tool,726553,ppolewicz,10283486,Backblaze,178797256,251831174,"My idea was to make it so our layer performs reading and hands off data to your layer, which can then decide what do do with it. This was the idea behind `AbstractDownloadDestination`. The current interface is fairly limited though and I am not sure if it provides everything that you actually need.

For instance, I would imagine that you will want to decouple the network readahead buffer from the actual read size. File objects are optimized for returning data that maybe needs several calls to the underlying layer, while in your case an opposite approach may be necessary: you want the underlying layer to perform one big read, while the data should be handed to your layer in multiple chunks as they arrive. For example, you'd like to read 1MB into memory, but return first 64KB (which the user has requested) as soon as possible (in such case lets assume that the latency is high and bandwidth is low).",{},,User,False
