16704,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-13 15:42:19+00:00,31667038,latchset/jwcrypto,3809868,michaelboulton,17146082,latchset,273238366,343958847,"I was doing some testing and it seems like if you force the protected header to be an empty dictionary it works:
```python
# testcase.py
import json
from jwcrypto.jwe import JWE
from jwcrypto.jwk import JWK

payload = json.dumps({
    ""test"": ""payload"",
})

jwe = JWE(payload)
jwe.objects[""protected""] = ""{}""

private_key = JWK.generate(kty='RSA', size=4096)
public_key = JWK()
public_key.import_key(**json.loads(private_key.export_public()))

header = {
    ""alg"": ""RSA-OAEP-256"",
    ""enc"": ""A256CBC-HS512"",
    ""typ"": ""JWE"",
}

jwe.add_recipient(public_key, header)

encrypted = jwe.serialize(compact=True)

decrypted = JWE()
decrypted.deserialize(encrypted, key=private_key)

print(json.loads(decrypted.plaintext.decode(""utf8"")))
```
```
$ python testcase.py
{'test': 'payload'}
```
I'm guessing this is unintended behaviour? I'm not sure but it seems like it's just using the value of the unprotected header if the protected header isn't present in the encrypted token (in `JWE._get_jose_header`)",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
