16852,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-21 08:21:44+00:00,35145177,BlueBrain/eFEL,3098670,wvangeit,1479142,BlueBrain,275158667,345950535,"This issue was actually also brought up by another user recently (by email).
There is indeed a problem with the detection of the AP onset for the first spike in these kind of traces. The algorithm picks the first points where the derivative threshold is crossed, and unfortunately in this case it's close to stimulus onset.
We were thinking of solutions, one of them being to search backwards from the peak of the spike. I didn't have time to look at it yet. It won't be a failsafe solution either, because by searching backwards, spikes that have a biphasic onset might cause problems.
If you have any other ideas, please let me know.",{},MEMBER,User,False
16853,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-09 09:50:12+00:00,35145177,BlueBrain/eFEL,5932954,christian-oreilly,1479142,BlueBrain,187489032,271244604,"(sorry for not following on this earlier; thanks @elisabettai for bringing
it back) I guess, there are two levels of thinking on that: (1) good API
architecture/usability (for the holy quest of the perfect software) vs. (2)
efficient use of BBP resources (in this case, Werner's time! ). So, in the
end, considering that, I'm also fine with your proposal (already supported
by Elisabetta) of adding SpikeCount_stimint. Also, in spirit of (2), I
personally have no immediate need for other *_stimint  features that I
cannot easily compute from SpikeCount_stimint (such as spiking frequency).

2017-01-09 10:34 GMT+01:00 elisabettai <notifications@github.com>:

