17113,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-25 12:34:06+00:00,1953389,stripe/stripe-python,14116796,olivierbellone,856813,stripe,185075635,256021901,"Interesting. I think what's happening here is that `deepcopy` casts `event` to a dict, but the nested object in the `data` key is still a `StripeObject`, and so the copy fails because we raise an exception ([here](https://github.com/stripe/stripe-python/blob/0381b7823990d4d56f2be7e0f3739ca3126a9ea4/stripe/resource.py#L147-L152)) when using an empty string for the value.
",{},,User,False
17115,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-15 17:33:49+00:00,1953389,stripe/stripe-python,96890,brandur,856813,stripe,176135402,247396491,"> Re 1: I see your point about Stripe being HTTPS only. The underlying libraries however, requests being the first one to cover, allow for both HTTP and HTTPS proxies. I can see use for both connection settings in either unit or deployment tests, where the Stripe state shall not be altered.

Ah, yes I see your point.

I wonder though if we should be trying to optimize the API for the ""95% path"" with respect to the fact that most people will probably just need to set a single proxy value.

I don't want to go crazy on taking advantage of duck typing, but I could imagine something along the lines of:

``` python
stripe.proxy = ""http://<user>:<pass>@<proxy>:<port>""
```

This would set that value for both HTTP and HTTPs. If you really need to pass options for both, you could set a dictionary like so:

``` python
stripe.proxy = {
    ""http"": ""http://<user>:<pass>@<proxy>:<port>"",
    ""https"": ""http://<user>:<pass>@<proxy>:<port>""
}
```

> Re 2: Totally! Will review the tests identifying the best place to hook and get proxy settings code coverage. If you happen to have specific test in mind, let me know in the meantime.

Awesome! Thank you.",{},,User,False
