17208,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-11 08:17:06+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,6702700,ej81,251374,spotify,147218577,208220259,"I want to run jobs on the cluster asynchronously without having an active child process on the login node for every job that is in the queue. The custom worker I use is basically the standard one, but I override _create_task_process() so that it submits the job without forking. In _handle_next_task() I synchronise the job status with the LSF queue before calling the superclass method.

It would probably be better to implement this in Task itself, but I don't think it can be done at the moment without modifying the Luigi code. It needs some refactoring of TaskProcess and Task. In that case the result_queue should be handled by Task and Task.run() should be allowed to return without considering the Task done or failed. If I have time I might try something and send another pull request to discuss.

@Tarrasch No, I didn't add a test case, but it could be useful indeed.",{},,User,False
