17247,IssueCommentEvent,2015-02-19 08:50:37+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,2393194,freider,251374,spotify,58077642,75016383,"@gpoulin To answer your first comment. Yeah, format chaining is definitely something I've been meaning to implement (that's a large reason for the pipe_* methods). I've been thinking about implementing a pipe operator on Format or something like that: `File(""some/path"", format=Text | Gzip)` (just brain storming here).
Using targets with non-default r/w modes was added quite recently to luigi as far as I can remember, so hopefully not too many people are opening targets in text mode, but it would definitely be a slightly backwards breaking change. If I'm not mistaken 'wb'/'rb' is the same as 'w'/'b' on *nix platforms at least.
What we could do in an interim to ease a transition to using formats for specifying text mode is to add a DeprecationWarning and add a Text format wrapper if you open a file in 't*' mode.

To answer your second comment:
* The fact that they are class methods is actually just backwards compatibility that haven't been touched in forever. We had some format specifiers as classes when we started prototyping, and then started introducing some formats as instances instead, but to avoid breaking places where we used the classes as formats (e.g. format=Gzip as opposed to format=Gzip()) I think I added the classmethod decorator as a quick hack to allow both using formats as classes and as instances. When defining new formats that could potentially take parameters (like encoding for a Text format) I would definitely encourage using instance methods instead and rely on duck typing. We might want to get rid of the class type formats as well, but I don't see it as urgent (mostly would make it a bit clearer that they can be used as instances instead).
* Yes, it's not pretty. If I remember correctly I made specialised methods for HDFS as an optimisation to since reading from HDFS in various formats can often be done using single command instead of piping through the normal commands (and for some formats we couldn't even do it using piping). I agree there is probably a cleaner way to do this - at the very least define the hdfs_reader/writers in the hdfs module, but I'm not sure we can cleanly decouple it from format. Any ideas?
",{},,User,False
