17529,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-13 16:18:00+00:00,7507548,materialsproject/fireworks,986759,computron,867057,materialsproject,94623762,120984451,"Because PyTask is supposed to be more flexible than the other tasks, and allow users to do *anything*. ScriptTask doesn't allow users to return a FWAction because it doesn't even call a Python function and catch the return object, it just calls a script (e.g. BASH script) for which it is impossible to catch back a Python object. Even in this scenario, for which I can't catch back a Python object and is expected to be much less dynamic than PyTask, someone can use the ScriptTask to write or append to a ""FWAction.json"" file that gets interpreted as a dynamic action.

Opposite to your view, I find your suggestion to ""chain tasks"" as an ""exercise in introducing unnecessary complexity"". Why should a user need to create an extra FireWork simply to query the DB for the stored value of the previous one and *return that again* to the next one? Is that how you would want your workflows to operate? It's certainly not something that I would ever want to have to do. Being able to return a FWAction in PyTask is completely reasonable and possible, it just makes PyTask much more attractive vs the alternative of writing your own FireTask via the API.",{},,User,False
