17680,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-22 18:52:57+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,165454905,248994701,"You'll want to modify the bootstrap scripts found in `letsencrypt-auto-source/pieces/bootstrappers`. You only need to worry about the Debian (`deb_common.sh`) and Red Hat (`rpm_common.sh`) scripts at this time. These are the only scripts that are officially supported that have OS packages available on some systems and don't already have a mechanism pointing users towards those packages (Arch already has [one](https://github.com/certbot/certbot/blob/master/letsencrypt-auto-source/letsencrypt-auto.template#L184)).

In each of these scripts, you'll need to use the package manager to identify if there's an OS package available. In most cases, you can simply search for a `certbot` package, however, the package is still named `letsencrypt` on Ubuntu Xenial. Be careful here as there's a `letsencrypt.sh` package out there which is a different project.

If you've determined that there is an OS package available, you need to tell the user. Probably the safest thing to do is here is simply print a message like I suggested in the original post on this issue and continue with the installation process.

After making changes to the bootstrap scripts, run `letsencrypt-auto-source/build.py` which will update `letsencrypt-auto-source/letsencrypt-auto`. Do not modify any of the `*-auto` scripts in the root directory. For legacy reasons, they are only modified during releases.

Don't hesitate to ask if you have any more questions.

cc @pde ",{},,User,False
