17735,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-23 14:37:21+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,124687,toolness,17889013,certbot,209554941,303418574,"Yep, that works!  You can actually even do `if False:` (this was actually recommended by guido in one of the GitHub mypy issues).

That said, I also have another strategy with regards to all the `type: ignore`s: rather than attempting to run mypy across the entire codebase, it might be more effective to run it only on certain files at first, so that you can incrementally bring strong typing to the whole project. This actually means you can *remove* the `type: ignore`s rather than continually add more, and it also means that you can run mypy on your whitelist of files during CI.

This is actually what I started doing yesterday, until I realized that mypy was already added in #4386. Let me know if you think we should use this strategy instead, or if you'd rather keep using your current one.",{},,User,False
